WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
 >> Hello everybody and welcome to our lecture on Cascading Style Sheet, CSS.

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:07.680
 Of course, this follows right on the heels of our HTML lecture.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:14.160
 And I'm gonna use a bunch of examples from webapplicationsforeverybody.com.

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:16.280
 And you can just bring these up in your browser.

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:22.000
 I love to place everything that we talk about in the context of the request

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:25.600
 response cycle cuz that's the whole web applications for everybody.

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:27.560
 You, of course, are out here.

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:32.560
 You do a click, it sends a request, a HTTP request, maybe talks to a database,

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:35.040
 gets some stuff back, sends some stuff back.

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:37.480
 This is the request response cycle right here.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:39.960
 And the thing that comes back is HTML.

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:43.560
 And then that is parsed, put into the document object model.

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:47.000
 And the thing that you then see, the pixels you see on your screen,

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:48.960
 are from the document object model.

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:51.280
 So that's what we've been doing so far.

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:54.640
 And so far, then at HTML lecture, we just talked about this.

00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:58.320
 What the format was when you parsed the response.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:01.040
 So what we're gonna talk about today is we're gonna talk about,

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:06.620
 in addition to that, we're gonna go and pull another file, a CSS file, CSS.

00:01:06.620 --> 00:01:08.920
 And that is gonna inform the document object model.

00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:11.640
 And it's gonna change how things look out here.

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:16.600
 And so we'll have some CSS in the HTML, but we'll also have some CSS in

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:19.840
 separate files that make separate request response cycles.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:23.480
 But so we're gonna be putting files like our HTML files in here and

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:25.240
 our CSS files in here.

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:27.520
 So we're gonna be serving them a little bit.

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:32.000
 But mostly what we're worried about is sort of the form,

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.600
 how to make the DOM look pretty, and that's sort of what CSS is all about.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:40.200
 So in addition, I would like you to install

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:45.800
 this thing called Web Developer from Chris Pedrick.

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:49.920
 Chris Pedrick has been doing this a long time before there were even developer

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:54.480
 consoles in browsers, and it's funny that the developer

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:56.480
 consoles don't do what this does.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:01.600
 And I don't use all of its features, but it has some wonderful features for CSS,

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:03.920
 in particular, turning on and off various styles.

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:07.720
 And so it's a great way to sort of dig through CSS issues,

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:10.080
 in addition to the web developer console.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:12.400
 And you can do a lot of sort of fine debugging, but

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:14.040
 there's some real nice stuff with web developer.

00:02:14.040 --> 00:02:18.640
 It's just a plug-in for your Safari or your Chrome or

00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:21.480
 your Mozilla browser or whatever.

00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:24.960
 So please install that, I recommend it, and

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:29.240
 some of the assignments actually require it.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:35.680
 So like I said in the HTML lecture, the HTML started out with,

00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:41.360
 we were just amazed in 1995 when we could see a page with a gray background and

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:48.960
 blue links, and it was lists, long lists of links, and the links turned purple.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:51.280
 And we would click on a link, and another page would come up, and

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:53.480
 we were like, holy mackerel, this is the future, right?

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:55.480
 And we were so happy.

00:02:55.480 --> 00:03:00.560
 And our curiosity was piqued, we did interesting things.

00:03:00.560 --> 00:03:08.560
 But in the 10, 15, almost 20 years since all that, it's become a business.

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:13.400
 And in business, the look and feel for the average non-nerd user,

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:15.960
 they don't care that there's a request-response cycle.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:18.560
 They just want to do a thing, talk to their friends or

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:21.640
 look up information or whatever.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:27.840
 And so the CSS is in the middle of this time frame.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:30.520
 The ability to precisely lay things out and

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:34.760
 make pages beautiful became super important for

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:38.680
 the web to take its sort of leap into commercial dumb.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:41.800
 So if you look at the Yahoo web page, for example,

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:43.960
 this is just a screenshot I took a while back.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:49.040
 They do studies as to how much white space is in between those two pieces.

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:51.240
 And they'll add a pixel and take away a pixel, and

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:53.080
 they'll see how their revenue goes.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:57.640
 And so these user experiences, these visual looks and

00:03:57.640 --> 00:04:02.480
 feels are highly tuned and highly sort of taken care of.

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:07.880
 And so CSS needed to be able to precisely have a pixel-perfect layout in

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:08.960
 every browser.

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:11.480
 And so CSS is a very, very precise thing.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:13.720
 HTML has become precise, but

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:17.400
 we don't wanna do our markup and layout in HTML.

00:04:17.400 --> 00:04:20.960
 I showed you tables previously, and in really early versions of HTML,

00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:24.960
 we used tables to create look and feel, and that was never good.

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:30.320
 So one of the things you can do with the Chris Pedrick web developer plugin is you

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:32.840
 can show a page without CSS.

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:38.000
 And what you should expect when you see a page without CSS is it's

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.160
 sort of beautiful even without CSS.

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:43.120
 It's beautiful in a logical and a structure.

00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:46.560
 And so here's my web applications for everybody website, right?

00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:47.880
 It's got some cool stuff.

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:50.480
 It's got these little things that go over there.

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:51.760
 It's got a little border.

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:54.040
 The color's gray here, and it's a little lighter gray, and

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:56.120
 this wraps around, and it looks really awesome, right?

00:04:57.280 --> 00:05:00.900
 Well, turn CSS off, and

00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:04.160
 you should still see a page that you could effectively navigate.

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:09.440
 It's like going back in time to a simpler time of, okay, I wanna see this.

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:12.360
 This is really a list of links at the end of the day, and there you go.

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:13.600
 It's a list of links.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:17.800
 And the default is I've already clicked on lessons, so lessons is purple now.

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:21.080
 And here's this video, and if you scroll up and down on this,

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:26.520
 I mean it's really fun to go to a website and turn CSS off and

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:30.120
 see how good their HTML developers are and how pretty it is.

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:33.800
 And so it's supposed to be pretty in a simple way.

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:37.160
 And what's nice about this is it really leads to good accessibility,

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:42.800
 meaning some people do not see the graphics, they hear the page read to them.

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:45.400
 And this way, this is how it's read.

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:49.840
 And the simpler and more beautiful and elegant your HTML is, the easier it is for

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:55.920
 a person who has reduced visual ability to understand your site.

00:05:55.920 --> 00:06:02.160
 And that is, I remember the joy of hearing from people who were using the web and

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:07.840
 gopher in the early days, how they all of a sudden could go anywhere and see anything

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:12.900
 and do anything in a way that visually impaired people could never do for

00:06:12.900 --> 00:06:14.960
 like hundreds of thousands of years.

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:16.520
 And it's joyful.

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:19.840
 And then what happened was is we ended up with this really nasty markup.

00:06:19.840 --> 00:06:23.200
 And then it was like the web was simple and they loved it.

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:26.400
 And then the web became ugly and nasty and HTML became nasty.

00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:30.480
 And they're like, the world is horrible because now you go to all these cool

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:34.560
 websites, but I can't go to these cool websites cuz I'm visually impaired.

00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:36.280
 And now we're back, we're back to that.

00:06:36.280 --> 00:06:39.720
 We're back to beautiful HTML, simple HTML, and

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:42.440
 then beautiful web pages and CSS is the main.

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:46.120
 Okay, I think I've done enough advertising for CSS and

00:06:46.120 --> 00:06:48.040
 accessibility and beautiful HTML.

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:53.640
 So ultimately, if you look at how this thing is assembled in your browser,

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:59.320
 there is an HTML page that is pulled down and then there is CSS.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:02.880
 Sort of both inside the document, sometimes there's CSS in the document.

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:04.120
 If you look at this, not that it matters,

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:06.240
 there's a little bit of CSS in that document.

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:09.920
 And then a whole bunch of other CSS that brings all the beauty to this.

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:12.400
 Sometimes it even takes some JavaScript and whatever.

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:15.960
 And so we understand that the HTML does not have the beauty in it.

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:18.920
 The beauty comes from the CSS.

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:22.480
 And that is part of what we try to do, is learn CSS.

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:25.320
 So if you're gonna be like a coder and you're not gonna be a graphic designer,

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:29.520
 you still need to know enough CSS so that you don't write horrible HTML, so

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:33.960
 that you know what a really good CSS developer is capable of doing on your

00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:35.000
 behalf.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:40.320
 And on large projects, including like Sakai project,

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:45.080
 which is a open source learning management system, this allows separation

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:50.920
 of concerns, and you can have people that specialize in the back end and the HTML.

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:54.120
 And then a web designer can, the web designer, so

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:57.800
 if you think of the developer usually, there's a back end.

00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:00.920
 And then they generate, from the back end, they generate the HTML, and

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:04.080
 then the designer will build the CSS.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:08.960
 The designer will often have skill enough to sort of tweak the HTML if

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:11.120
 the developer built bad HTML.

00:08:11.120 --> 00:08:14.400
 So they kind of meet in the middle of the HTML with the developer mostly being

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:17.720
 responsible for building the back end developer.

00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:24.220
 And then the front end designer can then tweak the HTML a little and

00:08:24.220 --> 00:08:25.280
 then tweak the CSS.

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:28.160
 And so the HTML is where the back end developer and

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:30.680
 the front end developer come together.

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:37.880
 But it means that you can, it means that you can have lots of people working and

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:42.280
 you can develop highly specialized skill sets in larger projects.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:48.120
 I know that my skill set is in this side, I am not skilled in this side, right?

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:53.160
 I can clunk my way through CSS and everything that you'll see is my CSS.

00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:55.400
 And you'll be like, whoa, that's not very good.

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:57.800
 And if it even looks pretty of mine, I'd probably use Bootstrap.

00:08:57.800 --> 00:09:01.840
 And I cheated and found a CSS framework and I didn't build it, I just did it.

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:04.840
 Now there are people who are smart enough to build Bootstrap.

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:08.440
 That's, and they're, they can build such gorgeous websites.

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:13.720
 And my job is to build beautiful HTML that then they can add CSS to and

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:15.920
 make it super gorgeous.

00:09:15.920 --> 00:09:19.200
 So the CSS basic syntax is different than HTML, right?

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:21.120
 HTML is less than and greater than.

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:23.640
 CSS has curly braces.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:26.960
 I don't really know who invented the first.

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:29.720
 I should find that out and go videotape that person.

00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:31.560
 But it has curly braces and semicolons, so

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:36.720
 it kind of looks like a little bit of C. And it's really a set of rules.

00:09:36.720 --> 00:09:41.840
 And it's not sequential, although the order does matter.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:46.160
 Because what comes later has more importance than what comes earlier in CSS.

00:09:46.160 --> 00:09:48.040
 But it's not like code that gets run.

00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:54.760
 And so the anatomy of a CSS rule is that there is some kind of a selector.

00:09:54.760 --> 00:09:59.160
 And in this case, the simplest selector is the tag that we want to affect.

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:00.600
 We want to affect the body tag.

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:03.960
 Now, there's only one body tag, but you could have a P for a P tag and

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:06.320
 say I would like to do this to all P tags.

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:12.400
 And so it's implicit, kinda like SQL, in that a body tag means for all body tags.

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:14.960
 There's an implicit loop for the whole document.

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:17.080
 And we'll see how to reduce that later to it, so

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:18.520
 it's not always the whole document.

00:10:18.520 --> 00:10:25.680
 But for now, a tag there by itself means every tag in this document.

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:31.360
 And then there's a series of rules, and so this is really when to apply.

00:10:31.360 --> 00:10:37.080
 This is sort of what aspect, and there's a whole list of aspects that you can have.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:39.920
 And then what you wanna do, I wanna make the font size 100%.

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:44.160
 I wanna use Arial, and then say in Serif, etc., etc., etc.

00:10:44.160 --> 00:10:49.240
 Holy mackerel, my little pen is undoing itself.

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:52.000
 And so then these end in a semicolon, and you can have a bunch of these, right?

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.760
 You can have just one, you can have more.

00:10:53.760 --> 00:10:58.560
 But that's the basic idea, is a CSS rule is go find a part of this document and

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:01.800
 paint it, I like to think of this as like, go find a thing and

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:04.920
 then run a paintbrush over top of it, that is this paintbrush.

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:08.040
 That is the paintbrush that you go select a piece of the document and

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:11.240
 then paint it yellow or paint it bold or whatever.

00:11:11.240 --> 00:11:12.680
 That's kinda how I think about it.

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:23.560
 Now, I'll admit, I'm really a very weak CSS developer, and I need a cheat sheet.

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:28.200
 And if I wanna do CSS, having even a single page cheat sheet

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:31.640
 is super helpful for me, just cuz I don't use it all the time.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:38.040
 And so the attributes like background color and the border-bottom,

00:11:38.040 --> 00:11:42.880
 for me, they're all very self-explanatory.

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:46.520
 They're really easy to understand, or if you don't understand them,

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:48.840
 you just Google and you go stack overflow.

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:52.360
 But for me, I'm like, is it border-bottom or bottom-border?

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:55.080
 I just can't remember that stuff, and so

00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:58.200
 I just have to have a cheat sheet whenever I work.

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:01.440
 And this is the one cheat sheet that I happen to like.

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:04.480
 And these are the kind of properties that we're gonna be playing with,

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:07.200
 the color, the background color, how to align it vertically,

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:12.200
 how to align it horizontally, padding, which is space on the sides, etc, etc, etc.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.560
 So there's just tons of CSS properties.

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:18.200
 And there's tons of great documentation on each of these CSS properties,

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:20.040
 with little samples all over the place.

00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:24.920
 And I have my own samples as well, that I'll do some recordings and

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:28.800
 show you, walk you through like line by line on my sample code as well.

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:32.160
 But this is the kind of stuff that we're gonna play with in CSS.

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:36.480
 So up next, we're gonna talk about how we connect CSS and HTML together.

